<dl id="n53035r"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n53" href="#n53035r">N53 (VI.B.46)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n53all.htm#n53035r"> 35(r)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> on hearts, brow, arms, / doorpost, gates, mezouza, / tephilim, <small>Orange</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n53035r"><li>FW 258.09 </li><li><a href="../../flex/kg/lexkg.htm#n53035r">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/kg/l39kg.htm#n53035r">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n53035r">MS BL 47477-186v</ms> </li><li>JJA 51:276 <a name="kad8" href="../../FF/fdra/kda.htm#kgd6">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/kg/kgd6.htm#n53035r">Draft: II.1&sect;7.6</a> </li> </ul><mm class="note">Note: Transferred to text via <a name="n52179i" href="n52all.htm#n52179i">N52 (VI.B.42):179(i)</a> and <a name="n52181a" href="n52all.htm#n52181a">N52 (VI.B.42):181(a)</a>. The Mezouza (Hebrew <i>mezuuzah</i> &mdash; doorpost) is a prophylactic and atrotropaic parchment inscribed on one side with Deut. 6.4-9, 11.13-21, and on the other with the divine name <i>Shaddai</i>. It is placed in a small wooden, metal, or glass box or casket, which is attached to the doorpost. The Tephillin (Hebrew <i>t&apos;phillim</i>: prayers) are two black-leather boxes fastened to leather straps containing Deut. 6.4-9, 11.13-21, and Ex. 13.1-16 inscribed on parchment. These phylacteries are laid on the arm and head of Jewish males of age at weekly morning service. </mm> </dd></dl>
